Introduction/ Motivation:

While the average human works day to day, people don't concern themselves with mundane matters such as global warming. Over the past century, the temperature of the Earth's surface has risen approximately 1.1 degrees Celsius, while that might not seem to be much but it has an everlasting effect on the quality of life and effects on different parts of the planet. Throughout this project, I plan to analyze the data on how temperatures have risen over the past 70 years in different countries throughout the world. We want to figure out if global warming is something people should take more seriously or if its just being exaggerated. By the end of the project we will figure out if the rate of temperature increase is something to be concerned about in our lifetimes.

Step 1: Importing Dependencies

The first step is to import the libraries that will allow us to extract, modify, analyze, and visualize data in a cleaner and efficient way. We will be using pandas and numpy to clean and modify and seaborn to create data visualizations. We are also using beautiful soup to scrape and parse the data into a neat and readable table format.

Every graph is linear with respect to the year. This shows the relationship between the temperature and the year meaning as time progresses the average change in temperature also increases. You can observe that for each of the graphs except for Hong Kong, each of these countries for the decade from 2010-2020 has experienced the highest temperature change to date.

Hypothesis testing

I will use Linear Regression to predict what the temperature change will be in the year 2100 for each of the countries.

In [14]:
x = America.iloc[:, 3].values.reshape(-1, 1)
y = America.iloc[:, 4].values.reshape(-1, 1)
regress = LinearRegression()
regress.fit(x, y)
y_pred = regress.predict(x)
plt.scatter(x, y)
plt.title('United States of America')
plt.ylabel('Average temperature change(°C)')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.plot(x, y_pred, color='black')
plt.show()
print({regress.predict([[2100]])[0][0]})

{3.35132461631499}

If the rate of Temperature Change continues to be the same the predicted Temperature change in the year 2100 will be 3.351325(°C) in the United States of America. In 2020, the average rate of temperature change is 1.331(°C). This means there will be an approximate 2(°C) increase in temperature change in the next 80 years.

Conclusion/ Insights Attained

After doing a thorough analysis of the change in temperature in multiple different countries throughout the world. It is safe to say that the change in temperature is something that people should start concerning themselves with. After observing the linear regression above, you can clearly see that there is an uptrend for every country that was graphed throughout the world. According to the Linear Regression model, The United States of America, Egypt, and South Africa are predicted to have an average temperature change of over 2(°C) in the next 80 years. At this rate, there will be catastrophic effects on the environment ranging from bigger and greater natural disasters, floods, droughts, etc. Additionally, as the temperature slowly rises throughout the world, it will also cause the condensed icebergs in Antarctica to slowly melt and cause an increase in the ocean's sea level causing floods for all the coasts throughout the world. It is important to use data science techniques such as machine learning to keep monitoring the temperature change around the world because we will see adverse impacts on human migration as they try to move more inland. Furthermore, countries like the United Arab Emirates and China have begun laying out artificial islands to have access to inhabitable land.
